Subject:    <a href="?t=95837887600022&r=1&w=2">Re: top level domains</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837786200025&r=1&w=2">rlk () think ! com  (Robert Krawitz)</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198905">1989-05-03 16:55:58</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626911&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626911&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

In article &lt;168@mirsa.inria.fr&gt;, huitema@mirsa (Christian Huitema) writes:
]One net result of registering a European organization under something like
]COM or ORG is that this organization will not be reachable through the
]standard European gateways. This is certainly OK for European branches of
]large multinational companies like IBM, which maintain large internal nets:
]for example our mail from "mirsa.inria.fr" (in Valbonne) to
]"some.one@dec.com" (also in Valbonne, next door actually) crosses the ocean
]twice, because the single recommanded gateway to ``DEC.COM'' lays somewhere
]in the USA. But I doubt that many European Universities would be ready to
]maintain a private link to the Internet, instead of sharing some regional or
]national facility...

You're confusing routing with naming.  These are entirely different
issues.

Granted, if you send mail to foobar@dec.com, and there's only one MX
record for dec.com, you're going to go through the US gateway.  But
this need not be the case; there could be multiple MX records for
dec.com with different addresses and equal priorities, and your mailer
can pick the best one based on its knowledge of the network topology,
and the user never sees this at all.

Another possibility is to have multiple dec.com names, and the user
picks the appropriate one.  For example, there could be decwrl.dec.com
(which actually exists), and valbonne.dec.com for the site you're
talking about.  If you want to send mail to someone at Valbonne, you
send it to foobar@valbonne.dec.com.

The whole idea is that names specify administrative entities, and not
network topologies.  If it's more desirable from an administrative
point of view for some of DEC's machines (the ones in France) to be
registered under the .fr domain, then name them that way.  But
registering DEC machines under .fr because mail sent to dec.com has to
cross the ocean a few times doesn't make much sense.
